"D'Anna B., Sellevåg S.R., Wirtz K., Nielsen C.J.","Photolysis study of perfluoro-2-methyl-3-pentanone under natural sunlight conditions",2005,"Environmental Science and Technology","39","22",,"8708","8711",,,10.1021/es048088u,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-27744530149&partnerID=40&md5=71dc6c61ac52b9ce4e766ee176f0e015","Department of Chemistry, University of Oslo, P.O. Box 1033, 0315 Oslo, Norway; Fundación Centro de Estudios Ambientales del Mediterraneo (CEAM), Parque Tecnológico, C/Charles R. Darwin 14, E-46980 Paterna, Valencia, Spain","D'Anna, B., Department of Chemistry, University of Oslo, P.O. Box 1033, 0315 Oslo, Norway; Sellevåg, S.R., Department of Chemistry, University of Oslo, P.O. Box 1033, 0315 Oslo, Norway; Wirtz, K., Fundación Centro de Estudios Ambientales del Mediterraneo (CEAM), Parque Tecnológico, C/Charles R. Darwin 14, E-46980 Paterna, Valencia, Spain; Nielsen, C.J., Department of Chemistry, University of Oslo, P.O. Box 1033, 0315 Oslo, Norway","The UV-vis and infrared absorption cross sections of perfluoro-2-methyl-3- pentanone (CF3CF2C(O)CF(CF3)2, 1,1,1,2,2,4,5,5,5-nonafluoro-4-(trifluoromethyl)-3-pentanone), has been obtained, and a photolysis study was carried out under natural sunlight conditions in the European simulation chamber, Valencia, Spain (EUPHORE). The photolysis loss rate, Jphotol, equaled (6.4 ± 0.3) × 10-6 s-1 in the period of 10-14 GMT, July 14, 2003 in Valencia (0.5 W, 39.5 N) and corresponded to an effective quantum yield of photolysis of 0.043 ± 0.011 over the wavelength range of 290-400 nm; the error limits correspond to 2σ from the statistical analyses. The atmospheric lifetime of CF3-CF2C(O)CF(CF3) 2 is estimated to be around 1 week, and the global warming potential of the compound is negligible. © 2005 American Chemical Society.",,"Error analysis; Global warming; Infrared radiation; Light absorption; Sun; Ultraviolet radiation; Atmospheric lifetime; Error limits; Simulation chamber; Warming potential; Photolysis; alkanone; perfluoro 2 methyl 3 pentanone; perfluoro compound; unclassified drug; photolysis; article; error; greenhouse effect; infrared spectroscopy; photolysis; quantum yield; reaction analysis; simulation; sunlight; ultraviolet spectroscopy; Flame Retardants; Fluorocarbons; Pentanones; Photolysis; Sunlight",,"Flame Retardants; Fluorocarbons; Pentanones; perfluoro-2-methyl-3-pentanone",,,,"Taniguchi, N., Wallington, T.J., Hurley, M.D., Guschin, A.G., Molina, L.T., Molina, M.J., Atmospheric chemistry of C2F5C-(O)CF(CF 3)2: Photolysis and reaction with Cl atoms, OH radicals, and ozone (2003) J. Phys. Chem. A, 107, pp. 2674-2679; Becker, K.H., (1996) The European Photoreactor EUPHORE; Final Report of the EC Project, , Contract EV5V-CT92-0059: Wuppertal, Germany; Magneron, I., Thevenet, R., Mellouki, A., Le Bras, G., Moortgat, G.K., Wirtz, K., A study of the photolysis and OH-initiated oxidation of acrolein and trans-crotonaldehyde (2002) J. Phys. Chem. A, 106, pp. 2526-2537; Volkamer, R., Platt, U., Wirtz, K., Primary and secondary glyoxal formation from aromatics: Experimental evidence for the bicycloalkyl-radical pathway from benzene, toluene, and pxylene (2001) J. Phys. Chem. A, 105, pp. 7865-7874; Klotz, B., Sorensen, S., Barnes, I., Becker, K.H., Etzkorn, T., Volkamer, R., Platt, U., Martin-Reviejo, M., Atmospheric oxidation of toluene in a large-volume outdoor photoreactor: In situ determination of ring-retaining product yields (1998) J. Phys. Chem. A, 102, pp. 10289-10299; Wenger, J.C., Le Calve, S., Sidebottom, H.W., Wirtz, K., Reviejo, M.M., Franklin, J.A., Photolysis of chloral under atmospheric conditions (2004) Environ. Sci. Technol., 38, pp. 831-837; Martinez, R.D., Buitrago, A.A., Howell, N.W., Hearn, C.H., Joens, J.A., The near UV absorption-spectra of several aliphatic-aldehydes and ketones at 300-K (1992) Atmos. Environ., Part A, 26, pp. 785-792; Moortgat, G.K., (2000) Evaluation of Radical Sources in Atmospheric, , Chemistry through 